The paper explores the ways in which people communicate in groups, using a structured random-walk model to capture key aspects of this process. The model is applied to three cases of increasing structural complexity, including philosophical texts, parliamentary debate, and online discussion forums. The paper therefore touches on a range of topics within computer science, including social networks (cs.SI), natural language processing (cs.CL), data mining (cs.SD), cybernetics (cs.CY), and social and information networks (cs.SOC).
